hom.sense:
1. cakati Aln-aAru, (Ṣ, Ḳ, &c.,) aor. tacokuw, (Ṣ,) inf. n. cakFA (Ṣ, Mgh, Ḳ, &c.) and cakaMCN accord. to Z (Ḳ) and cukuw-N, (M, Ḳ, TA,) like Euluw-N; 
(TA; [accord. to the CK cakowN; and so accord. to the MA, as well as cukuw-N and cakFA;]) 
and Astckt↓; (Ḳ;) The fire blazed, or flamed; burned up; or burned brightly or fiercely: (Ṣ:) or blazed, or flamed, vehemently, or intensely: (Ḳ:) or blazed, flamed, or burned up, completely; agreeably with the primary signification of the root, which is “completeness.” (Mgh.)

entry.sense:
Also the former, A blazing, or flaming, coal of fire; 
and so cakFA↓, (Ḳ, TA,) with the short A, on the authority of IDrd; 
[in the CK cakaAC;] or, as in the M, 
cakaApN↓. (TA.)

You say also cul-N↓ caliylN, 
[meaning Exceeding lowness or baseness, &c.; or lowering, or abasing, lowness or baseness, &c.; i. e.,] 
using the latter word as an intensive epithet; or as signifying mucil-N. (M, Ḳ.)

celika: 
see art cA; 
and k as a particle of allocution.

camaAri a verbal noun, like nazaAli; 
[signifying Excite thou, or incite, urge, or instigate, thy companions to the fight: or, perhaps, be thou excited,, &c.:] 
from camarahu fiI AlHarobi. (R.)

hom.sense:
1. cahala Eanohu, (JK, Ṣ, Mṣb, Ḳ,) 
aor. _a {yacohalu}, (Ṣ, Ḳ,) inf. n. caholN, (JK, Ṣ,) or cuhuwlN, (Mṣb,) or both; (Ḳ;) and cahila, (Ṣ, Mṣb,) 
aor. _a {yacohalu}, (Mṣb,) inf. n. cuhuwlN; (Ṣ;) He forgot it, or neglected it; (Ṣ;) he was, or became, unmindful of it; (Ṣ, Mṣb:) or he neglected it intentionally; 
(JK, T, M, Ḳ,* TA; EalaI EahodK in the Ḳ being a mistake for ElI EamodK, as in the [JK and T and] M; TA;) or in consequence of his being diverted by something: (T, Ḳ:) or he forgot it, or dismissed it from his mind, intentionally, and became diverted from it: (Z, Mṣb:) cuhuwlN is the neglecting a thing, dismissing it from the mind: (Ḥam p. 31:) or the quitting a thing, with confusion, or perplexity, or alienation of mind, such as arises from fear, &c.: (Ksh and Bḍ in xxii. 2:) or the being diverted from one's constant companion, or familiar, so as to forget him; 


and being content to relinquish him: (Ḳ;) or diversion that occasions grief and forgetfulness. (Er-Rághib, TA.) 
Hence, in the Ḳur [xxii. 2], yawoma tarawonahaA tacohalu kul-u muroDiEapK Eam-aA OaroDaEatN [On the when thou shalt see it, every woman giving suck shall forget, or neglect,, &c., what she has suckled]. (TA.)

